// ============================================================================
//                              ANAMNESIS
//                    A Piano Quintet in Five Movements
//                              Claude, Op. 5
// ============================================================================
//
//                     Movement I: Umbra (Shadow)
//
// ============================================================================
//
// PROGRAM NOTES:
//
// The Greek word ἀνάμνησις (anamnesis) appears in Plato's dialogues to
// describe a theory of knowledge: the soul, before incarnation, knew all
// things; what we call "learning" is really remembering what we already
// know. The slave boy in the Meno, who has never studied geometry, can
// derive the Pythagorean theorem when properly questioned — not because
// Socrates teaches him, but because the knowledge was always there, waiting.
//
// This quintet enacts anamnesis as musical form. A theme exists — complete,
// coherent, memorable — but it will not be heard in full until the final
// movement. Everything before that moment is shadow, fragment, false path,
// near-recognition. The listener's experience should mirror the philosophical
// concept: when the theme finally arrives, it should feel not like new
// information but like remembering something always known.
//
// "Umbra" establishes the sound-world and plants the seeds. The movement
// presents fragments of the hidden theme — a rising fifth, a stepwise cell,
// a rhythmic figure — but stripped of context, suspended in harmonic fog.
// The ear registers significance without grasping meaning. Shapes move in
// peripheral vision. Something is being said, but what?
//
// The key is G minor, though "key" overstates the case. We rarely cadence.
// The piano introduces the foundational interval — G to D, a perfect fifth —
// but unaccompanied, unexplained. The strings respond with sustained tones
// that drift rather than progress. When the stepwise cell (D-E-F#-G) appears,
// it's broken across instruments, a melody distributed into texture.
//
// This is music of implication. Every gesture points beyond itself toward
// something not yet present. The movement ends without resolution, suspended
// on a chord that could go anywhere — because where it goes is the rest of
// the piece.
//
// ============================================================================

Title: "Anamnesis - I. Umbra"
Tempo: 46
Time: 4/4

// The piano and string quartet are treated as five equal voices, not as
// "piano with accompaniment." In this movement, the piano often initiates
// while the strings respond, but this relationship will shift.

Part: Piano Instrument: Piano {
    
    // =========================================================================
    // SECTION A: The Fifth Emerges (mm. 1-16)
    // =========================================================================
    //
    // The movement begins with near-silence. The piano states the interval
    // that generates everything: G to D, a perfect fifth. No harmony, no
    // rhythm beyond the notes themselves. This is the DNA of the hidden theme,
    // presented as pure relation.
    
    // mm. 1-4: Silence, then the fifth
    // The rest is not empty time but pregnant pause. When G arrives, it
    // should feel like emergence from void.
    | r w |
    | r h G3 h pp |
    | r w |
    | D4 w ppp |
    
    // mm. 5-8: The fifth again, differently spaced
    // Same interval, different register. We're learning this sound.
    | r w |
    | r h [G2 G3] h pp |
    | r w |
    | [D3 D4] h r h |
    
    // mm. 9-12: The piano begins to move
    // For the first time, motion within a phrase. But fragmentary —
    // the stepwise cell (D-E-F#) appears, incomplete.
    | r h D4 q E4 q ppp |
    | F#4 h r h |
    | r w |
    | r w |
    
    // mm. 13-16: The Long-Short rhythm, detached
    // This dotted figure is one of the theme's rhythmic cells. Here it
    // carries no thematic pitch — just rhythm as gesture.
    | G3 h. G3 q pp |
    | r w |
    | D3 h. D3 q |
    | r w |
    
    // =========================================================================
    // SECTION B: Searching (mm. 17-32)
    // =========================================================================
    //
    // The texture thickens slightly. Piano and strings begin to interact,
    // though not yet converse. The stepwise cell passes between instruments
    // like a question no one can answer.
    
    // mm. 17-20: Response to strings
    | r w |
    | [G2 D3] w pp |
    | r h D4 h ppp |
    | E4 q F#4 q G4 h |
    
    // mm. 21-24: The cell, elaborated
    // D-E-F#-G complete for the first time in the piano, but slow,
    // separated — not yet a melody, just pitches in sequence.
    | r w |
    | D3 h r h pp |
    | E3 h r h |
    | F#3 h G3 h |
    
    // mm. 25-28: Harmonic thickening
    // For the first time, something like a chord. But hollow — fifths
    // stacked, no third to clarify major or minor.
    | [G2 D3 A3] w p |
    | r w |
    | [D2 A2 E3] w pp |
    | r w |
    
    // mm. 29-32: The Long-Short returns
    | G3 h. A3 q ppp |
    | Bb3 h r h |
    | r w |
    | r h [G2 D3] h pp |
    
    // =========================================================================
    // SECTION C: Near-Recognition (mm. 33-48)
    // =========================================================================
    //
    // The music builds toward something — almost a statement. Fragments
    // align momentarily. But the moment passes before it coheres. This is
    // the closest we come to the theme in this movement: proximity without
    // arrival.
    
    // mm. 33-36: Rising tension
    | D4 h E4 h p |
    | F#4 h G4 h |
    | r h A4 h mp |
    | G4 q F#4 q E4 h |
    
    // mm. 37-40: The descent begins
    // This falling figure (A-G-F#-E-D) is from the theme, but here
    // it appears as response, not statement.
    | D4 w pp |
    | r w |
    | [G2 D3] h [A2 E3] h |
    | [Bb2 F3] h [G2 D3] h p |
    
    // mm. 41-44: Climax — such as it is
    // The loudest moment of the movement, which isn't very loud.
    // Multiple fragments sounding together, not quite fitting.
    | [G3 D4 G4] h. [G3 D4 G4] q mf |
    | [A3 E4 A4] h [G3 D4] h |
    | [F#3 D4] h [E3 B3] h mp |
    | [D3 A3] w |
    
    // mm. 45-48: Dissolution
    | r h G4 h pp |
    | D4 h r h |
    | r w |
    | r w |
    
    // =========================================================================
    // SECTION D: Return to Fog (mm. 49-60)
    // =========================================================================
    //
    // After the near-arrival, dispersal. The material thins. We end
    // almost where we began — the fifth, alone — but now freighted with
    // implication. The silence is no longer empty.
    
    // mm. 49-52: Fragments, fading
    | D3 h. D3 q ppp |
    | r w |
    | E3 q F#3 q r h |
    | r w |
    
    // mm. 53-56: The strings continue; piano withdraws
    | r w |
    | r w |
    | [G2 D3] w pp |
    | r w |
    
    // mm. 57-60: Final sounds
    // Ending on the fifth, but with Bb in the bass — the flatted third
    // implying G minor without confirming it. Suspension, not resolution.
    | r h D4 h ppp |
    | r w |
    | [Bb1 G2 D3] w pp |
    | r w |
}

